The loading amount of drug MTX was calculated from the samples through device UV–Vis spectroscopy (Fig. 7
                        ). The findings showed that adding nanoparticles to chitosan polymer reduces drug loading. These observations showed that the presence of nanoparticles may reduce the porosity of the chitosan polymer, and as a result, with an increase in the percentage of nanoparticles, the drug loading decreases. The drug release pattern was examined at pH = 5 and pH = 7.4 in Fig. 8
                        , with these specific pH values selected to simulate the typical pH of the tumor microenvironment and the normal pH of the blood, respectively. The results indicate that the release rate of MTX was influenced by pH, time, and nanoparticle concentration. The release rate of MTX from MTX/CS is slower in physiological environments (pH = 7.4) compared to acidic conditions (pH = 5). Due to the solubility of CS in acidic aqueous solutions, it exhibits the fastest drug release rate. Furthermore, the amino group present in CS (with a pKa value of approximately 6.5) undergoes hydrolysis under acidic conditions, resulting in the production of positive ionic compounds (which is particularly relevant considering the acidic pH and negative charge of cancer tissues) [40]. Furthermore, the investigation of drug release from chitosan in both acidic and alkaline environments revealed an initial burst release and uncontrolled drug release behavior from this carrier. To address this issue, this study was conducted to investigate the mixing of different percentages of nanoparticles in chitosan polymer. Upon evaluating the drug release at pH = 5, it was observed that the drug release rate increased as the percentage of nanoparticles was raised. This phenomenon can be attributed to the increased protonation of amino groups within the chitosan polymer chains, resulting in an augmented presence of positive charges. This, in turn, led to enhanced electrostatic interaction between the chitosan polymer and graphene quantum dots, ultimately promoting a more substantial drug release [41]. Moreover, under pH = 7.4 conditions, nanocomposites exhibited diverse, distinct drug release profiles. Considering that chitosan-based hydrogel beads were prepared in an alkaline environment. With increasing content of MGQD, the release ratio of hydrogel beads decreases. The effective intermolecular interaction between the MGQD and CS matrix may lead to the dense structure of the MTX/CS-MGQD hydrogels, resulting in the decrease of the drug release ratio from MTX/CS-MGQD hydrogel beads. However, in acidic environments, electrostatic repulsion occurs between the polymer chains and causes more release of the drug [42]. To minimize drug-associated side effects and restrict release within the body's physiological environment (pH = 7.4), selecting nanocomposite MTX/CS-MGQD 15 %, which demonstrates a low drug release rate, is the optimal choice. Similarly, at pH = 5, the MTX/CS-MGQD 15 % nanocomposite offered advantages such as controlled release, a low burst release rate, and approximately 80 % drug release, making it the optimal choice.
